1. Break the CPU Bottleneck (Threaded Video I/O)

The Problem: In test_yolo.py, cap.read() and out.write() are completely synchronous. Every time your script reads a frame, the GPU has to pause and wait for your CPU to decode the .mkv file. That is why your GPU is at 12%—it spends 88% of its time waiting for the CPU.
The Fix: We can use a background thread to read video frames into a queue. While the GPU is doing the AI math on Frame 1, the CPU is already pre-fetching Frame 2, 3, and 4 in the background.

    Impact: This alone could double or triple your current FPS.

2. Add a "Quality Gate" (Blur Detection)

The Problem: In a live video, people move, and motion blur happens. Currently, if YOLO detects a face, you send it to FaceNet—even if it's horribly blurred. A blurry face generates a bad embedding, which might result in an "Unknown" or a false positive, messing up your Counter voting logic.
The Fix: Before passing face_crop_bgr to FaceNet, we calculate the sharpness of the crop using the Laplacian variance.
Python

# Add this right after you crop the face
sharpness = cv2.Laplacian(face_crop_bgr, cv2.CV_64F).var()
if sharpness < 50.0:  # Adjust threshold based on your video quality
    continue # Skip this frame for this person, wait for a clearer shot

    Impact: Massive boost to attendance accuracy; prevents bad data from polluting the vote.

3. Upgrade from PyTorch (.pt) to TensorRT (.engine)

The Problem: You are running the standard PyTorch weights (yolov8n-face.pt). While fast, PyTorch is fundamentally a research framework with some overhead.
The Fix: Since you have an NVIDIA GPU, you can export that YOLO model into a TensorRT engine. TensorRT specifically optimizes the neural network architecture for your exact RTX A4000 chip. You literally just run yolo export model=yolov8n-face.pt format=engine half=True in your terminal, and load the resulting .engine file in your code.

    Impact: Usually provides a 2x to 4x speedup for YOLO inference with zero loss in accuracy.

4. Batch Processing in train_yolo.py

The Problem: Your training script loops through your dataset images one by one, sending a single face to the GPU at a time (unsqueeze(0)). GPUs hate single tasks; they love bulk work.
The Fix: When processing a person's folder, gather all the cropped faces into a list, run torch.cat() to combine them into one batch (just like you do in your testing script!), and send them through FaceNet all at once.

    Impact: Your database building/updating phase will finish in seconds rather than minutes.








